+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Virtualization May Break Vista DRM                                 |
|   from the couldn't-they-have-just-said-that dept.                 |
|   posted by Zonk on Saturday June 23, @23:53 (Microsoft)           |
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/24/0348233              |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Nom du Keyboard writes "An article in Computerworld posits that the
reason Microsoft has flip-flopped on allowing all versions of Vista to be
run in virtual machines, is that [0]it breaks the Vista DRM beyond
detection, or repair. So is every future advance in computer security
and/or usability going to be held hostage to the gods of Hollywood and
Digital Restrictions Management? 'Will encouraging consumer
virtualization result in a major uptick in piracy? Not anytime soon, say
analysts. One of the main obstacles is the massive size of VMs. Because
they include the operating system, the simulated hardware, as well as the
software and/or multimedia files, VMs can easily run in the tens of
gigabytes, making them hard to exchange over the Internet. But DeGroot
says that problem can be partly overcome with .zip and compression tools
-- some, ironically, even supplied by Microsoft itself.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/24/0348233

Links:
    0. http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic&articleId=9025466&pageNumber=1


